                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="20509" author="klr8" created="Fri, 27 Oct 2006 18:32:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This indeed needs to be scheduled for resolution ASAP. Probably 1.0.1. A solution similar to that implemented by Juergen in core Spring is probably the way to go: make the ThreadLocal variant used configurable at the level of the FlowExecutor.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20562" author="klr8" created="Tue, 31 Oct 2006 00:55:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve looked at this a little bit and maybe we should just drop the ExternalContextHolder entirely. For the moment it&apos;s only used by the SessionBindingConversationManager to get access to the ExternalContext. Arguably we should pass the ExternalContext into the ConversationManager.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20663" author="klr8" created="Mon, 6 Nov 2006 02:37:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;After some more pondering on the issue, I think we should just switch to a normal ThreadLocal. That has 3 benefits:&lt;br/&gt;
1) Simple&lt;br/&gt;
2) No API impact&lt;br/&gt;
3) The flexibility of a ThreadLocal remains (if some internal CoversationManager implementation artifact needs the ExternalContext, it can get access to it without the ExternalContext needing to be passed around everywhere)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The need of an InheritableThreadLocal seems like a very exotic case, so I prefer we just keep it simple and go with ThreadLocal. If some ConversationManager implementation needs to expose the ExternalContext to threads it is spawning it can still do so by either just passing the object in or using it&apos;s own InheritableThreadLocal holder.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20725" author="klr8" created="Fri, 10 Nov 2006 06:21:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;ExternalContextHolder now just uses a ThreadLocal instead of an InheritableThreadLocal.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
